{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox artwork |image_file =RussianSchoolroom-NormanRockwell.jpg |painting_alignment = |image_size = |title = Russian Schoolroom |alt = |medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] |artist = [[Norman Rockwell]] |year = 1967 |height_metric = 40 |width_metric = 93 |height_imperial = |width_imperial = |metric_unit=cm |imperial_unit=in |city = |museum = [[National Museum of American Illustration]] }} '''''Russian Schoolroom''''' (1967) — also known as '''''The Russian Classroom''''' and '''''Russian Schoolchildren''''' — is an [[oil on canvas]] painting created by American [[illustrator]] [[Norman Rockwell]] (1894–1978) and commissioned by ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' magazine. It depicts Russian schoolchildren in a classroom with a bust of Soviet leader [[Vladimir Lenin]].
The painting is shown at the [[National Museum of American Illustration]].
==Description== ''Russian Schoolroom'' depicts a group of seated and attentive Soviet schoolchildren looking towards the viewer’s left, presumably at a teacher outside the visual frame. A [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] of V.I. Lenin with strewn flowers is, however, partially visible there. The children wear [[Young Pioneer organization of the Soviet Union|red Young Communist neckerchiefs]] and a Russian slogan on the wall behind them exhorts them to “Study and Learn”. One pupil on the right, however, looks away to the viewer’s right, like a typical schoolboy losing focus and finding something more interesting to see outdoors.
==Background== ''Russian Schoolroom'' was published in the October 3, 1967, edition of ''Look'' as part of a series of articles on life in the [[Soviet Union]]. Rockwell had visited School No. 39 in Moscow where he drew puppy sketches on a chalkboard.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://2neat.com/magazine/product/look-magazine-october-3-1967/ |title=LOOK Magazine – October 3, 1967 |website=2neat.com |accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> Reference photos of the Moscow classroom with pupils, taken as a model for Rockwell’s final painting, reveal that the inattentive pupil is actually paying close attention to the teacher, with eyes front.<ref name=ackerman/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://collection.nrm.org/search.do?id=550181&db=object&view=full |title=Reference photo for Education (38883) |website=Norman Rockwell Museum |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> It has been suggested that in changing this detail, Rockwell slightly subverted the image to make a subtle political point in favor of non-conformity.<ref name=ackerman>{{cite web |last=Ackerman |first=Mark |date=March 12, 2011 |url=http://www.culturevoyage.co.uk/norman-rockwell-does-it-matter-if-its-art/ |title=Norman Rockwell – Does it Matter if it’s Art? |website=culturevoyage.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426043613/http://www.culturevoyage.co.uk/norman-rockwell-does-it-matter-if-its-art/ |archive-date=April 26, 2012 |via=archive.org}}</ref> Additional reference photos show Rockwell himself sitting in that student's seat, apparently demonstrating a distracted look, which the student then emulated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collection.nrm.org/search.do?id=550369&db=object&view=full |title=Reference photo for Education (38917) |website=Norman Rockwell Museum |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://collection.nrm.org/search.do?id=550386&db=object&view=full |title=Reference photo for Education (38918) |website=Norman Rockwell Museum |accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>
==Theft and litigation== The painting was stolen during an exhibit at a small art gallery in [[Clayton, Missouri]], in June 1973.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19031262/rockwell_work_is_stolen_from_clayton/ |title=Rockwell Work Is Stolen From Clayton Shop |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |page=13 |date=June 26, 1973 |accessdate=April 7, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1988, it turned up and was sold at an auction in New Orleans for about $70,000. [[Steven Spielberg]] bought the painting from [[Judy Goffman Cutler]], a noted [[art dealer]] who specialized in American illustrators, in 1989 for $200,000. A member of his staff spotted the painting on a [[FBI]] web listing of stolen works of art and the authorities were immediately notified.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.today.com/id/17430445#.WRU5AFKZOiI |title=Stolen Rockwell found in Spielberg’s collection |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 3, 2007 |via=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|''Today'']]}}</ref> By 2009, the painting was in the custody of the [[United States District Court for the District of Nevada|U.S. District Court in Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Boehm |first=Mike |date=October 6, 2009 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2009/10/spielberg-and-the-rockwell-painting-that-got-away.html |title=Steven Spielberg and the Norman Rockwell painting that got away |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=2010-02-17}}</ref> The court decided in 2010 that the painting belonged to Cutler, who has added it to the collection on display at the [[National Museum of American Illustration]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Salit |date=April 18, 2010 |url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/ROCKWELL_DECISION_04-18-10_G5I4SSM_v8.352d873.html |newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]] |title=Judge vindicates Newport art dealer over sale of painting |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100422212203/http://www.projo.com/news/content/ROCKWELL_DECISION_04-18-10_G5I4SSM_v8.352d873.html |archivedate=April 22, 2010 |via=archive.org}}</ref>
